[[File:Kamiishizu Misanzai Kofun zenkei-2.JPG|280px|thumb|center|Full view of the tumulus (foreground: front mound, background: rear mound)]]
'''Kamiishizu Misanzai Kofun''' (上石津ミサンザイ古墳), also known as the '''Ishizugaoka Kofun''' (石津ヶ丘古墳), is a {{ill|Zenpokoenfun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Nishi-ku, Sakai|ja|西区 (堺市)|12=draft|12=draft}}, Sakai City, Osaka Prefecture. It is situated in the southern part of the {{ill|Mozu Kofun Cluster|ja|百舌鳥古墳群|1=Mozu Tombs|12=draft|12=draft}} and is one of the largest tumuli in Japan, with a mound length of 365 meters. The {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft|12=draft}} has designated it as the "'''Mozu Mimihara Minami Mausoleum'''" (百舌鳥耳原南陵), attributing it to {{ill|Emperor Richu|ja|履中天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, the 17th emperor of Japan. It is part of the {{ill|World Cultural Heritage|ja|文化遺産 (世界遺産)|12=draft|12=draft}} site "Mozu-Furuichi Kofun Group: Mounded Tombs of Ancient Japan."

== Overview ==
The name "Misanzai" is thought to be a phonetic variation of the term "misasagi" (陵), meaning imperial mausoleum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crd.ndl.go.jp/reference/modules/d3ndlcrdentry/index.php?page=ref_view&id=1000261206|title=Etymology of Kofun Names|publisher=National Diet Library|accessdate=2021-11-19}}</ref> Historical maps from the Edo period refer to the site as "Richu Tennō-ryō" (履中天皇陵). Prior to being incorporated into Sakai City, the area was part of {{ill|Shinseki Village|ja|神石村|12=draft|12=draft}}, Senboku District.

Kamiishizu Misanzai Kofun is a {{ill|Zenpokoenfun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft|12=draft}} constructed on the western edge of a plateau, with the front mound facing south. Its placement and orientation were likely chosen to make the tumulus visible from Osaka Bay.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/911/00000153|title=Richu Tennō-ryō Kofun / Component Asset / World Heritage|publisher=Agency for Cultural Affairs|accessdate=2021-11-22}}</ref> 

The mound consists of three tiers and features protrusions (造り出し) on both sides of the constricted area, although the eastern protrusion is now significantly eroded.<ref name=":0" /> The total length of the tumulus is 365 meters, making it the third-largest in Japan after {{ill|Daisenryō Kofun|ja|大仙陵古墳|1=Daisenryō Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} (Emperor Nintoku's mausoleum) and {{ill|Honmyōyama Kofun|ja|誉田御廟山古墳|1=Konda Gobyoyama Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} (Emperor Ōjin's mausoleum). The rear mound has a diameter of 205 meters and a height of 27.6 meters, while the front mound measures 235 meters in width and 25.3 meters in height.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.sakai.lg.jp/kanko/rekishi/dkofun/Ranking/zenkoku.html|title=Ranking of Kofun Sizes in Japan|publisher=Sakai City Cultural and Tourism Bureau|accessdate=2021-11-22}}</ref>

Excavations and aerial surveys have revealed the presence of circular platforms at the tops of the front and rear mounds, a unique feature among keyhole-shaped tumuli. These platforms may have held burial facilities.<ref name=":0" />

The tumulus is surrounded by a large moat, with a width of approximately 62 meters at the front mound and 70 meters at the rear mound. While the current moat is single-layered, earlier surveys suggest it originally had an outer moat, possibly a dry moat.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mozu Kofun Cluster Research Volume 1|publisher=Sakai City Board of Education|date=2008}}</ref>

Artifacts recovered from the site include a variety of haniwa, such as house-shaped and quiver-shaped haniwa, as well as Sue pottery. The presence of a massive quiver-shaped haniwa, standing 1.4 meters tall, suggests the tumulus was constructed in the early 5th century.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mozu Kofun Cluster Research Volume 1|publisher=Sakai City Board of Education|date=2008}}</ref>

== Satellite Tumuli ==
Several smaller tumuli, believed to be satellite tombs (陪塚), surround the main tumulus. Of these, only the {{ill|Shichikannon Kofun|ja|七観音古墳|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Terayama Minamiyama Kofun|ja|寺山南山古墳|12=draft|12=draft}} remain intact today. Historical records suggest that other satellite tombs, such as the {{ill|Shichikanyama Kofun|ja|七観山古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}, once existed and were contemporaneous with the main tumulus.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mozu Kofun Cluster Research Volume 1|publisher=Sakai City Board of Education|date=2008}}</ref>

== World Heritage ==
In 2019, Kamiishizu Misanzai Kofun was registered as part of the World Cultural Heritage site "Mozu-Furuichi Kofun Group: Mounded Tombs of Ancient Japan."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/special_content/hlinkJ|title=Mozu-Furuichi Kofun Group - Mounded Tombs of Ancient Japan|publisher=Agency for Cultural Affairs|accessdate=2021-11-14}}</ref>

== Access ==
* **JR Hanwa Line**: A 6-minute walk (500 meters) from {{ill|Uenoshiba Station|ja|上野芝駅|12=draft|12=draft}} to the Richu Tennō Mausoleum.
* **Nankai Koya Line**: From Sakaihigashi Station, take a bus to "Nankyo-dori Yoncho" (南陵通四丁) and walk 5 minutes.

